Kern 2.0
========

A hobby x86 kernel written in C and x86 assembly, built from scratch without
any standard library. Boots via GRUB (Multiboot 1), runs in 32-bit protected
mode with a higher-half layout, and supports preemptive multitasking with
user-space processes running in ring 3.


Build Requirements
------------------

  - i686-elf-gcc     (cross-compiler targeting bare-metal x86)
  - i686-elf-ld      (cross-linker)
  - GRUB             (grub-mkrescue)
  - xorriso          (ISO generation)
  - python3          (mkinitrd.py initrd builder)
  - QEMU (optional)  (qemu-system-i386, for running locally)


Building and Running
--------------------

  make              Build kern.iso (kernel + initrd)
  make run          Build and launch in QEMU (GTK display + serial on stdio)
  make run-headless Build and launch with no display (serial on stdio)
  make run-debug    Launch with QEMU interrupt/CPU-reset logging to qemu-debug.log
  make clean        Remove all build artefacts


Project Structure
-----------------

  boot/             Multiboot header, paging bootstrap, kernel entry point
  cpu/              GDT (6 entries + TSS), IDT, ISR stubs, PIC, exceptions
  drivers/          VGA text driver, PS/2 keyboard, PIT timer, serial (COM1)
  fs/               Virtual filesystem (VFS) backed by the initrd
  kernel/           kernel_main, shell, ELF32 loader, kprintf, panic
  lib/              (empty — libc-equivalents are in kernel/ or inline)
  mm/               PMM (bitmap), VMM (4 KB paging, per-task PDs), heap
  proc/             Task/scheduler, context switch, syscall gate, usermode entry
  tools/            mkinitrd.py — packs ELF binaries into an initrd image
  userland/         user.ld linker script, lib.h (tiny libc), test.c


Memory Layout
-------------

  Physical 0x00100000  Kernel boot trampoline (LMA = VMA here)
  Virtual  0xC0101000  Kernel .text start  (higher-half, LMA = phys 0x101000)
  Virtual  0xC0107000  .bss: boot page directory (4 KB)
  Virtual  0xC0108000  .bss: boot kernel stack (16 KB, stack_top = 0xC010C000)
  Virtual  0xC012E000  .bss: pre-allocated kernel page tables (PT_PREALLOC × 4 MB)
  Virtual  0xC0136000  .bss: kernel page directory
  Virtual  0xC0137014  _kernel_end → heap starts here (2 MB, kmalloc/kfree)
  Virtual  0xBFFEC000  User stack base  (16 KB per process, just below kernel)
  Virtual  0xBFFF0000  USER_STACK_TOP (initial ring-3 ESP)


Kernel Subsystems
-----------------

Boot (boot/boot.s)
  Multiboot-compliant entry. Before paging: maps the first 4 MB identity and
  kernel VMA via 4 MB PSE PDEs, enables paging, jumps to the higher-half entry.
  After paging: sets the boot stack (16 KB in .bss) and calls kernel_main.

GDT  [cpu/gdt.c]
  Six entries: null, kernel code (ring 0), kernel data (ring 0), user code
  (ring 3), user data (ring 3), and a 32-bit TSS descriptor. The TSS holds
  SS0/ESP0 which the CPU reads on every ring-3 → ring-0 transition; it is
  updated per-task by tss_set_kernel_stack() before each user-mode entry and
  after every context switch.

IDT + PIC  [cpu/idt.c, cpu/isr.s]
  The 8259 PIC is remapped so IRQs 0-15 land on vectors 0x20-0x2F. The IDT
  holds 32 exception gates (ring 0 only), 16 hardware IRQ gates (ring 0 only),
  and one syscall gate at vector 0x80 (DPL=3, callable from ring 3). EOI is
  sent before calling the C handler so the PIC is unmasked while the handler
  runs — important because the timer handler may block inside task_yield().

PS/2 Keyboard  [drivers/keyboard.c]
  Scan-code set 1 translated on IRQ 1. Characters land in a 256-byte circular
  ring buffer. keyboard_getchar() busy-waits with hlt until a character arrives.

PIT Timer  [drivers/timer.c]
  Channel 0 programmed to 1000 Hz (1 ms per tick). A registered callback
  (scheduler_tick) fires on each IRQ 0 to advance the preemptive scheduler.

VGA Text Driver  [drivers/vga.c]
  Writes to 0xB8000. Supports newlines, scrolling, backspace, and colour.

Serial  [drivers/serial.c]
  COM1 at 9600 baud, used for debug output alongside the VGA display.

PMM  [mm/pmm.c]
  Parses the Multiboot memory map and maintains a bit-per-frame bitmap covering
  up to 4 GB. The first 1 MB, the kernel image, the initrd, and the heap are
  permanently reserved. pmm_alloc_frame() returns the lowest free 4 KB frame;
  pmm_free_frame() returns it.

VMM / Paging  [mm/vmm.c]
  Switches from the boot PSE map to proper 4 KB pages during vmm_init(). The
  kernel PD maps 32 MB of physical memory at 0xC0000000 (8 pre-allocated page
  tables). Per-task page directories share these kernel PDEs (indices 768-1023)
  and have private user-space PDEs (indices 0-767). Key operations:
    vmm_create_pd()     new empty PD with shared kernel half
    vmm_destroy_pd()    free all user pages, page tables, and the PD itself
    vmm_clone_pd()      deep-copy for fork() — new PTs and new page frames
    vmm_map_in_pd()     map a page in an arbitrary (non-current) PD
    vmm_switch()        load a PD by writing its physical address to CR3

Heap  [mm/heap.c]
  A linked-list free-list allocator in a 2 MB region immediately after the
  kernel image. First-fit; kfree() coalesces adjacent free blocks.

ELF Loader  [kernel/elf.c]
  Loads PT_LOAD segments from an ELF32 executable into a given page directory,
  maps the user stack (16 KB below USER_STACK_TOP), and returns the entry point.

VFS + initrd  [fs/vfs.c]
  The initrd is a custom packed binary (produced by tools/mkinitrd.py) containing
  named file entries. vfs_open/read/close give read-only access to the files.
  Used by the kernel to load ELF binaries on demand.

Task / Scheduler  [proc/task.c, proc/scheduler.c]
  Preemptive round-robin scheduler with a 10 ms quantum (10 × 1 ms timer ticks).
  Each task_t holds a kernel stack (8 KB embedded in the struct), a page-directory
  physical address (cr3), saved ESP, and per-task open-file table (8 FDs).
  Task states: RUNNING, READY, SLEEPING, DEAD.

  task_create()   kernel-mode task (own PD, kernel stack)
  task_exec()     ELF task: load binary, enter ring-3 via enter_usermode()
  task_fork()     clone current task: vmm_clone_pd + fork_enter_user assembly
  task_waitpid()  block until a child exits, then reap it
  task_sleep()    sleep for N ms (SLEEPING state, woken by scheduler_tick)
  task_exit()     mark DEAD, free user address space, yield

Context Switch  [cpu/context_switch.s]
  switch_context() saves/restores ebx, esi, edi, ebp, eflags on the kernel
  stack and swaps ESP. fork_enter_user() builds a popa+iret frame from a
  saved registers_t so a forked child resumes exactly at the fork() call site
  with eax=0.

Syscalls  [proc/syscall.c]
  int 0x80, eax = syscall number, ebx/ecx/edx = arguments, return in eax.

    0  exit      terminate calling task
    1  write     write bytes to fd (fd 1 = VGA stdout; pipe write ends also work)
    2  open      open a file from the initrd by name
    3  read      read from fd (fd 0 = keyboard; pipe read ends block until data)
    4  close     close a file descriptor
    5  getpid    return the calling task's PID
    6  sbrk      grow user heap by N bytes; returns old program break
    7  fork      clone task (deep-copy address space); returns 0 in child
    8  waitpid   wait for a child PID to exit
    9  exec      ebx=path, ecx=cmdline — replace image; sets up argc/argv
   10  sleep     sleep for N milliseconds
   11  pipe      ebx=int[2] out-ptr; fills [0]=read fd, [1]=write fd
   12  dup2      ebx=old_fd, ecx=new_fd — duplicate fd (used for redirections)
   13  getdent   ebx=index, ecx=buf, edx=bufsz — return nth initrd filename

Userland  [userland/]
  Tiny freestanding libc (lib.h): syscall wrappers, printf, puts, strlen,
  strcmp, strncmp, strncpy, memset, memcpy, malloc/free/realloc.
  Compiled with -ffreestanding -nostdlib, linked at 0x400000.

  Programs packed into the initrd:
    sh      Userland shell: reads commands, fork+exec's programs, waitpid.
            Supports pipelines (cmd1 | cmd2 | ...).  Launched automatically.
    echo    Prints argv[1..] separated by spaces.
    cat     Reads files (or stdin) and writes to stdout.
    ls      Lists initrd files via SYS_GETDENT.
    wc      Counts lines, words, and characters from stdin or files.
    grep    Prints lines containing a literal pattern (from stdin or files).
    test    fork/waitpid/sleep/malloc smoke test.

  argc/argv: elf_setup_argv() writes the argument frame onto the user stack
  via vmm_virt_to_phys before the task starts; _start receives (argc, argv)
  in standard cdecl form.


Userland Shell (sh)
-------------------

  The userland shell launches automatically.  Type any initrd filename to run
  it.  Built-ins: help, exit.  Pipelines with | are supported.

  Examples:
    $ ls
    $ echo hello world
    $ cat test
    $ test
    $ ls | wc
    $ ls | grep sh

Kernel Shell (fallback)
-----------------------

  Reached when the userland shell exits.  Commands:

  help              List available commands
  clear             Clear the screen
  echo <text>       Print text
  ticks             Milliseconds since boot
  meminfo           Physical memory and heap statistics
  ps                List all tasks with state and PID
  sleep <ms>        Kernel-side sleep (shell blocks)
  ls                List files in the initrd
  exec <file>       Load and run an ELF from the initrd; shell waits for exit
  usertest          Quick ring-3 smoke test (inline asm, no ELF)
  version           Kernel subsystem summary
  halt              cli + hlt


Known Issues / Work in Progress
--------------------------------

  None known.  Recent fixes:

  - TSS ESP0 / fork+sleep crash: root cause was a reentrancy bug in
    task_yield().  When called with IF=1 (direct path: task_sleep, task_wait)
    the timer IRQ could fire between "current = next" and switch_context,
    causing the nested scheduler_tick to read the wrong current and corrupt
    saved stack pointers.  Fixed by saving IF and issuing CLI at the start of
    task_yield, then restoring IF (per-task, from the saved value on the kernel
    stack) after switch_context and tss_set_kernel_stack.

  - Initial kernel stack frame order in task_alloc() was wrong: eflags and ebx
    were swapped, so new tasks started with IF=0.  Fixed; frame now matches the
    pop order in switch_context (popf first, ret last).
